```xml

    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>
</project>
```

To control the brightness of the LCD screen, you can use a 10 K Ohm potentiometer [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The potentiometer is connected to the Arduino board, and the second pin of the potentiometer is connected to pin 3 of the LCD.

Once the connections are made, you can write the code to read the temperature from the temperature sensor and display it on the LCD screen. The code can be written using the Arduino IDE, and it involves using the LiquidCrystal_I2C library to control the LCD screen [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)].

To support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens in Apache Airflow, you'll need to configure the `auth_backend` and `auth_type` settings in your `airflow.cfg` file.

Here's an example configuration code snippet that you can use as a starting point:
```python
[core]
auth_backend = airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory

[azure_active_directory]
client_id = <your_client_id>
client_secret = <your_client_secret>
tenant_id = <your_tenant_id>
authority = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>
token_endpoint = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>/oauth2/v2.0/token
```
Replace the placeholders with your actual Azure AD application settings:

* `<your_client_id>`: The client ID of your Azure AD application.
* `<your_client_secret>`: The client secret of your Azure AD application.
* `<your_tenant_id>`: The tenant ID of your Azure AD tenant.

You'll also need to install the `azure-identity` and `azure-common` libraries, which are required by the `airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory` backend. You can install them using pip:
```bash
pip install azure-identity azure-common
```
Once you've updated your `airflow.cfg` file and installed the required libraries, you should be able to use Azure AD SSO tokens to authenticate with your Airflow instance.
